Here is a step-by-step guide to writing OmniScore, designed for a beginner just learning music.

-----

## 🎹 Step 1: Set Up the Music File

First, we need to create a header that tells the computer what this piece is called and who wrote it.

  * You start with the word `meta` and use curly brackets `{}` like a folder to hold your information.

<!-- end list -->

```
meta {
  title: "My First Song"
  composer: "My Name"
}
```

  * You then define the instruments. Since we are using a **Piano**, we define the two hands (the voices) that will play the music.

<!-- end list -->

```
group "Piano" symbol=brace {
  def rh "Right Hand" style=standard clef=treble  // Higher notes
  def lh "Left Hand"  style=standard clef=bass   // Lower notes
}
```

-----

## 🎶 Step 2: Define the Starting Rules

Before the first measure, we need to set the time. This is like telling a runner when to start and how long the track is.

  * The **time** tells you how many beats are in each measure (like $4/4$ time means 4 beats).
  * The **tempo** tells you how fast those beats are (like 60 beats per minute).

<!-- end list -->

```
meta { time: 4/4, tempo: 120 }
```

-----

## 🎵 Step 3: Write the Notes (Pitch and Octave)

Every note you write needs two things: **the letter** (A, B, C, D, E, F, G) and **the octave** (which "level" of the piano the note is on).

  * **Pitch/Octave Naming:** We use the system where **Middle C** (the C closest to the middle of the piano) is always called `c4`.
      * Notes below it (like the next C down) are `c3`.
      * Notes above it (like the next C up) are `c5`.
  * **Sharps and Flats:** Use a `#` right after the note letter for a sharp (e.g., `f#4`). Use a `b` for a flat (e.g., `eb4`).

| Note Name | Location on Piano |
| :--- | :--- |
| `c3` | C below middle C |
| `c4` | Middle C (the center) |
| `c5` | C above middle C |
| `f#4` | F-sharp above middle C |

-----

## ⏱️ Step 4: Define the Rhythm (Duration)

After every note, you must use a colon `:` followed by a number to tell the computer **how long** to hold that note. This is the note's duration.

| Note Name | Code | Beats (in 4/4 time) |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Whole Note** | `:1` | 4 beats |
| **Half Note** | `:2` | 2 beats |
| **Quarter Note** | `:4` | 1 beat |
| **Eighth Note** | `:8` | $1/2$ beat |
| **Dotted Note** | `:4.` | 1.5 beats (add a dot `.`) |

-----

## 🎼 Step 5: Write the Measures

Now we put everything together, measure by measure. Each measure must start with the keyword `measure` and use a pipe `|` at the end to close the measure.

### A. Single Notes (Melody)

In this example, we'll write a simple melody in the **Right Hand (rh)**: four quarter notes (C-D-E-F) followed by a half note (G).

```
measure 1
  rh: c4:4 d4:4 e4:4 f4:4 |  // C, D, E, F (all 1 beat)
  lh: r:1                 |  // The Left Hand rests for the whole measure (r:1)
measure 2
  rh: g4:2 c4:2 |  // G (2 beats) and C (2 beats)
  lh: r:1       |
```

### B. Chords (Multiple Notes at Once)

To play notes at the same time (a chord), you put them inside **square brackets** `[]`.

In this example, the **Left Hand (lh)** plays a C-major chord (`c3, e3, g3`) for two beats while the Right Hand rests.

```
measure 3
  rh: r:2                 |
  lh: [c3 e3 g3]:2 [c3]:2 | // Left Hand plays C-E-G (2 beats), then just C (2 beats)
```

-----

## 🎹 Full Example (Combining Steps)

Here is a small, complete piece using all the elements:

```
meta {
  title: "OmniScore Practice"
  composer: "Learner"
}
group "Piano" symbol=brace {
  def rh "Right Hand" style=standard clef=treble
  def lh "Left Hand"  style=standard clef=bass
}
meta { time: 4/4, tempo: 80 }

measure 1
  rh: c4:4 e4:4 g4:4 c5:4 | // RH plays C-E-G-C (4 quarter notes)
  lh: c2:1                | // LH plays C an octave down (Whole Note)
measure 2
  rh: d5:2 f5:2 |          // RH plays D and F (two half notes)
  lh: g2:1      |          // LH plays G (Whole Note)
```

**Your next step is always determined by the last measure you wrote.** Just keep adding measures until your song is finished\!
